\b\fs26 \cf0 Making skins
\b0\fs22 \
ByteController skin files are bundles with the "bcskin" extension.\
\
\'95 Make your skin in an image editing applicaton\
\'95 Create a new directory, for example "MySkin"\
\'95 Create a new Property List file called "Info.plist". Either:\
	\'95 Use the Property List Editor app included in XCode\
	\'95 Copy a Info.plist file from some other skin, and change the values using Text Edit\
\
These are the supported keys:\
	"Author"			- The author of the skin\
	"CopyrightText"	- A short text to display who has the copyright of the skin\
	"Created"			- The date the skin was created\
	"Description"		- A short text describing the skin\
	"Name"			- The name of the skin\
	"Notes"			- Additional information. Credits, Homepage, etc.\
	\
"Author", "Created" and "Name" are required.\
\
\'95 Create a subdirectory called "Resources"\
\'95 Slice your skin image, and put the slices in the Resources directory:\
	"play" 			- Play Button\
	"pause"			- Pause Button\
	"next"			- Next Song Button\
	"previous"			- Previous Song Button\
\
For the down state images, append "Down" to the filename. For example "playDown". Down state images are required. Omitting them can cause unreliable behavior.\
\
You can use any image files supported by Cocoa. Tagged Image File Format ("TIFF") or Portable Network Graphics ("PNG") are recommended the recommended formats. Alpha channel is supported.\
\
\'95 Go back to your "MySkin" directory, and append a "bcskin" extension.\
\
You should now have a bundle called "MySkin.bcskin" with a subdirectory called "Resources" with all your image files. To try the skin, simply double-click your new skin.\
\

\b\fs26 Changing default behavior
\b0\fs22 \
ByteController uses Apple Script to control iTunes. You can change the behavior of the buttons by customizing the scripts files. You could for example make ByteController control some other jukebox application. Or perhaps even control a slideshow application. You must know basic Apple Script to do this. Right/control click the ByteController application icon. Select "Show Package Contents". Proceed to the Contents/Resources/ subdirectory. Here you will find four script files:\
